  "Math_Problem": "In a sports meeting a total of $m$ medals were awarded over $n$ days. On the first day one medal and $\\frac{1}{7}$ of the remaining medals were awarded. On the second day two medals and $\\frac{1}{7}$ of the remaining medals were awarded, and so on. On the last day, the remaining $n$ medals were awarded. How many medals did the meeting last, and what was the total number of medals ? Instead of determining the total number of medals and the number of days the meeting lasted, simply find $k = c - 35$, where $c$ is the constant term in the linear particular solution derived from the sequential awarding process for the remaining medals. Do there exist $\\{x,y\\}\\in\\mathbb{Z}$ satisfying $(2x+k)^{3}+k=y^{4}$? Instead of determining whether there exist integers such that an odd integer cubed plus one equals a fourth power, simply find $m = y + 1$, where $y$ is the base of the fourth power in an integer solution to the equation. Determine which integers $n > m$ have the property that there exists an infinite sequence $a_1$ , $a_2$ , $a_3$ , $\\dots$ of nonzero integers such that the equality \\\\[a_k + 2a_{2k} + \\\\dots + na_{nk} = 0\\\\] holds for every positive integer $k \\\\geq m$.",
